 stupas, to argue that the historical Buddha does not really exist in the imagination of most people, including Buddhists. In this book, she sets out to plug this gap in our understanding of Buddhism, illuminating and eliminating many misconceptions along the way. Gender, religion, and caste in early India come alive in this richly scholarly yet accessible and imaginative account of society in the time of the Buddha. This is a book for students, teachers, and everyone interested in the living universe of India 2500 years ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aHistory : World History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : History of Religion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849124040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438491240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438491240/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles